:"1413","1323":"1323","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","circa 1292":"1292","1353":"1353","about 1323":"circa 1323","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hornby, Lancashire, England":"Hornby, Lancashire, England","Glodwich, Lancashire, England":"Atherton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England":"Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England","Hindley, Lancashire, England":"Hindley, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"–1353":"–1353","1290–1333":"1290–1333","1316–Male":"1316–Deceased","1312–1373":"1312–1373","1323–1413":"1323–1413","1250–1292":"1250–1292","1271–Female":"1271–Deceased","before 1330":"before 1330","1373":"1373","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1413":"1413","1323":"1323","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","circa 1292":"1292","1353":"1353","about 1323":"about 1323","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hornby, Lancashire, England":"Hornby, Lancashire, England","Glodwich, Lancashire, England":"Atherton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England":"Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England","Hindley, Lancashire, England":"Hindley, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Atherton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place near Manchester named Atherton, from the Old English personal name <i>Æthelhere</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’.","English: habitational name from Hatherton, Staffordshire, from Old English <i>haguthorn</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘the hill where hawthorn grows’.","English (East Anglia): topographic name from Middle English <i>at ther doune</i> ‘(dweller) on the hill’ (Old English <i>æt thǣre dūne</i>). Through confusion of <i>-don</i> and <i>-ton</i>, <i>Attherdoune</i> was altered to <i>Atherton</i>, <i>Adderton</i>, and <i>Atterton</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":24,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":55,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":80,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":93,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":102,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Atherton was born in Hindley, Lancashire, England as the daughter of Sir Hugh de Atherton and Agnus Molyneux. She married Robert Neville before 1330, in Hindley, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1353, in Hornby, Lancashire, England."},"et":{"–1353":"–1353","1290–1333":"1290–1333","1316–Male":"1316–Surnud","1312–1373":"1312–1373","1323–1413":"1323–1413","1250–1292":"1250–1292","1271–Female":"1271–Surnud","before 1330":"enne 1330","1373":"1373","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1413":"1413","1323":"1323","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","circa 1292":"1292","1353":"1353","about 1323":"umbes 1323","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hornby, Lancashire, England":"Hornby,